e University). He is currently pursuing his PhD in africa <em>studies</em> at the Centre for Gender and Africa <em>Studies</em>, University of the Free State in South Africa. He was a DAAD Masters Fellow (2010-2011), a SSRC Doctoral Proposal Development Fellow (2019-2020), and currently an SSRC Dissertation Completion Fellow (2020-2021).","matchLevel":"full","fullyHighlighted":false,"matchedWords":["case","studies"]}}}],"nbHits":34,"page":0,"nbPages":2,"hitsPerPage":20,"exhaustiveNbHits":true,"exhaustiveTypo":true,"exhaustive":{"nbHits":true,"typo":true},"query":""case studies"","params":"query="case studies"&facetFilters=%5B%5B%22competition_year%3A2018%22%2C%22competition_year%3A2019%22%2C%22competition_year%3A2020%22%2C%22competition_year%3A2021%22%5D%2C%5B%22post_type%3Afellow%22%5D%5D","index":"wp_searchable_posts","renderingContent":{},"processingTimeMS":12,"processingTimingsMS":{"_request":{"roundTrip":30},"afterFetch":{"format":{"highlighting":3,"snippeting":5,"total":9},"total":10},"fetch":{"total":1},"getIdx":{"load":{"total":1},"total":1},"total":12},"serverTimeMS":13}]}

{"results":[{"hits":[{"post_id":10395,"post_type":"fellow","post_type_label":"Fellows","post_title":"Tendai Chari","post_excerpt":"","post_date":1633278512,"post_date_formatted":"October 3, 2021","post_modified":1633278514,"comment_count":0,"menu_order":0,"post_author":{"user_id":1,"display_name":"ssrc_admin","user_url":"","user_login":"ssrc_admin"},"images":[],"permalink":"https://www.ssrc.org/fellows/8b4e1782-5680-e811-80cb-005056ab0bd9/","post_mime_type":"","taxonomies":[],"taxonomies_hierarchical":[],"is_sticky":0,"archived":"false","exclude_search":"false","program_types":"","competition_year":"2018","project_title":"Diaspora Media and their Entanglement in Homeland Conflicts: Mapping Discourses of Conflict and Peacebuilding","project_description":"","award_title":"","award_institution":"University of Venda","award_department":"","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/%7BB27C1ADD-0DE7-E611-80C4-005056AB0BD9%7D.jpg","related_competitions":"Book Manuscript Completion Grants","fellow_topics":"","authors":null,"primary_author":null,"publish_date":null,"publisher":null,"s3azure_image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/%7BB27C1ADD-0DE7-E611-80C4-005056AB0BD9%7D.jpg","s3azure_pdf_url":null,"type":null,"post_year":2021,"content":"Tendai Joseph Chari is a senior lecturer in the Media Studies Department, School of Human and Social Sciences, University of Venda, South Africa. He holds a PhD in Media Studies from the University of Witwatersrand, South Africa, and a Master’s in Media and Communication Studies from the University of Zimbabwe. Dr. Chari is widely published in the field of Media Studies and his research interests span a number of specializations, such as political communication, environmental communication, media and development, media ethics, and new media and society. Some of his publications have appeared in the Journal of African Media Studies, African Identities, Communication: South African Journal for Communication Theory and Research, Ecquid Novi: Journal of African Media Studies, and the Journal on Media and Communications. His latest publication, “Rethinking Climate Change Communication Strategies: The Case for Indigenous Media” in Indilinga – African Journal of Indigenous Knowledge Systems, gives a critical appraisal of current practices on climate change communication and advocates for the fusion of indigenous modes of communication and the mass media in generating deeper knowledge on climate change in Africa. He has presented at over forty-five local and international conferences in over thirty-three countries. Dr. Chari is an active member of the Academic and Non-Fiction Authors’ Association of South Africa (ANFASA). He serves on the editorial boards of international academic journals such as the Western Journal of Mass Communication, Journal on Media and Communications (JMC), and DOT-Comm Journal based in the Czech Republic. Previously, he served as the Chairman of the Zimbabwe Television (ZTV), was a board member of the Zimbabwe Broadcast Holdings (ZBH) (2004-2006), as well as a member of the Media Commission (MIC) in Zimbabwe (2007-2008).","record_index":0,"objectID":"10395-0","_snippetResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Tendai Chari","matchLevel":"none"},"content":{"value":"Tendai Joseph Chari is a senior lecturer in the Media <em>Studies</em> Department, School of Human and Social Sciences, University of Venda, South Africa. He holds a PhD in Media <em>Studies</em> …","matchLevel":"partial"}},"_highlightResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Tendai Chari","matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[]},"content":{"value":"Tendai Joseph Chari is a senior lecturer in the Media <em>Studies</em> Department, School of Human and Social Sciences, University of Venda, South Africa. He holds a PhD in Media <em>Studies</em> from the University of Witwatersrand, South Africa, and a Master’s in Media and Communication <em>Studies</em> from the University of Zimbabwe. Dr. Chari is widely published in the field of Media <em>Studies</em> and his research interests span a number of specializations, such as political communication, environmental communication, media and development, media ethics, and new media and society. Some of his publications have appeared in the Journal of African Media <em>Studies</em>, African Identities, Communication: South African Journal for Communication Theory and Research, Ecquid Novi: Journal of African Media <em>Studies</em>, and the Journal on Media and Communications. His latest publication, “Rethinking Climate Change Communication Strategies: The <em>Case</em> for Indigenous Media” in Indilinga – African Journal of Indigenous Knowledge Systems, gives a critical appraisal of current practices on climate change communication and advocates for the fusion of indigenous modes of communication and the mass media in generating deeper knowledge on climate change in Africa. He has presented at over forty-five local and international conferences in over thirty-three countries. Dr. Chari is an active member of the Academic and Non-Fiction Authors’ Association of South Africa (ANFASA). He serves on the editorial boards of international academic journals such as the Western Journal of Mass Communication, Journal on Media and Communications (JMC), and DOT-Comm Journal based in the Czech Republic. Previously, he served as the Chairman of the Zimbabwe Television (ZTV), was a board member of the Zimbabwe Broadcast Holdings (ZBH) (2004-2006), as well as a member of the Media Commission (MIC) in Zimbabwe (2007-2008).","matchLevel":"full","fullyHighlighted":false,"matchedWords":["case","studies"]}}},{"post_id":9779,"post_type":"fellow","post_type_label":"Fellows","post_title":"Flora Hasunga","post_excerpt":"","post_date":1633278410,"post_date_formatted":"October 3, 2021","post_modified":1633278412,"comment_count":0,"menu_order":0,"post_author":{"user_id":1,"display_name":"ssrc_admin","user_url":"","user_login":"ssrc_admin"},"images":[],"permalink":"https://www.ssrc.org/fellows/a0cc8eed-007b-e811-80cb-005056ab0bd9/","post_mime_type":"","taxonomies":[],"taxonomies_hierarchical":[],"is_sticky":0,"archived":"false","exclude_search":"false","program_types":"","competition_year":"2018","project_title":"CONTRIBUTION OF CUSTOMARY LAND TITLES ON RURAL WOMEN'S ECONOMIC EMPOWERMENT IN TANZANIA: A CASE OF MBOZI DISTRICT,SONGWE REGION, TANZANIA","project_description":"The topic of the study is Contribution of Customary Land Titles on Rural Women's Economic Empowerment in Tanzania: A Case of Mbozi District, Songwe Region. Specifically the study intends to identify factors influencing unequal ownership of customary land titles to men and women; to examine the effect of customary land titles on rural women's economic empowerment.  To examine the level of economic empowerment of women before and after customary land ownership. According to TDHS (2016: P 328) indicates that, women who own land in rural area alone are 44% compared to 16% for urban areas. Despite this evidence of rural women who own customary land titles yet very few studies focus on its contribution to women's economic empowerment. Questionnaire survey, Checklist interview guide for Focus Group Discussions and key informants will be used in collecting data. Quantitative data will be analyzed by SPSS and content analysis for qualitative data analysis.","award_title":"","award_institution":"Open University of Tanzania","award_department":"DEPARTMENT OF SOCIOLOGY AND SOCIAL WORK","image_url":"https://ssrccrmdocuments.blob.core.windows.net/website-documents/contact/hasunga-flora.png","related_competitions":"Next Generation Social Sciences in Africa: Doctoral Dissertation Proposal Fellowship","fellow_topics":"","authors":null,"primary_author":null,"publish_date":null,"publisher":null,"s3azure_image_url":"https://ssrccrmdocuments.blob.core.windows.net/website-documents/contact/hasunga-flora.png","s3azure_pdf_url":null,"type":null,"post_year":2021,"content":"Flora Hasunga is a sociologist, gender specialist, and social development expert specialized in social security, gender-based violence, and women’s economic empowerment. She is an assistant lecturer of the Mwalimu Nyerere Memorial Academy in the Department of Gender Studies since 2008. Her primary areas of teaching are gender and development, development studies, sociology, gender mainstreaming, women’s empowerment, gender analytical frameworks, and gender policy formulation. Currently, she is a PhD student in Sociology. Her PhD academic research assesses “The Contribution of Customary Land Titles on Rural Women’s Economic Empowerment in Tanzania, A case of Mbozi District, Songwe Region.” Hasunga has a degree of arts in sociology and a Master’s Degree in development studies from the University of Dar es Salaam. She worked as an assistant training officer with the Word Vision based in Tanzania in a project of creating awareness to religious and community leaders on gender-based violence and good governance at Dar es Salaam Region. She also presented research on gender-based violence with intimate partners at the University of Dar es Salaam. Also, she worked as a consultant in reviewing strategic plan 2017-2021 of Mkuranga District, Dar es Salaam region. In 2018 and 2019, she attended two workshops of doctoral dissertation prroposal development fellows prepared by SSRC in the African Program at Makerere University, Kampala, Uganda, and at The United States International University Nairobi, Kenya. She is ready to work as a researcher, consultant, project planner, and trainer on gender, women’s rights.","record_index":0,"objectID":"9779-0","_snippetResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Flora Hasunga","matchLevel":"none"},"content":{"value":"… is an assistant lecturer of the Mwalimu Nyerere Memorial Academy in the Department of Gender <em>Studies</em> since 2008. Her primary areas of teaching are gender and development, development <em>studies</em>, sociology …","matchLevel":"partial"}},"_highlightResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Flora Hasunga","matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[]},"content":{"value":"Flora Hasunga is a sociologist, gender specialist, and social development expert specialized in social security, gender-based violence, and women’s economic empowerment. She is an assistant lecturer of the Mwalimu Nyerere Memorial Academy in the Department of Gender <em>Studies</em> since 2008. Her primary areas of teaching are gender and development, development <em>studies</em>, sociology, gender mainstreaming, women’s empowerment, gender analytical frameworks, and gender policy formulation. Currently, she is a PhD student in Sociology. Her PhD academic research assesses “The Contribution of Customary Land Titles on Rural Women’s Economic Empowerment in Tanzania, A <em>case</em> of Mbozi District, Songwe Region.” Hasunga has a degree of arts in sociology and a Master’s Degree in development <em>studies</em> from the University of Dar es Salaam. She worked as an assistant training officer with the Word Vision based in Tanzania in a project of creating awareness to religious and community leaders on gender-based violence and good governance at Dar es Salaam Region. She also presented research on gender-based violence with intimate partners at the University of Dar es Salaam. Also, she worked as a consultant in reviewing strategic plan 2017-2021 of Mkuranga District, Dar es Salaam region. In 2018 and 2019, she attended two workshops of doctoral dissertation prroposal development fellows prepared by SSRC in the African Program at Makerere University, Kampala, Uganda, and at The United States International University Nairobi, Kenya. She is ready to work as a researcher, consultant, project planner, and trainer on gender, women’s rights.","matchLevel":"full","fullyHighlighted":false,"matchedWords":["case","studies"]}}},{"post_id":9777,"post_type":"fellow","post_type_label":"Fellows","post_title":"Chad Brevis","post_excerpt":"","post_date":1633278410,"post_date_formatted":"October 3, 2021","post_modified":1633278412,"comment_count":0,"menu_order":0,"post_author":{"user_id":1,"display_name":"ssrc_admin","user_url":"","user_login":"ssrc_admin"},"images":[],"permalink":"https://www.ssrc.org/fellows/97cc8eed-007b-e811-80cb-005056ab0bd9/","post_mime_type":"","taxonomies":[],"taxonomies_hierarchical":[],"is_sticky":0,"archived":"false","exclude_search":"false","program_types":"","competition_year":"2018","project_title":"Communicative Freedom in a Digital Democracy: Political and Economic Resistance to Free Speech and the Rise of Digital Activism.","project_description":"My thesis focuses on violent conflict in protests, media and the politics of representation. It critically explores the idea of South Africa as a constitutional democracy and how free speech legislation at once promotes and inhibits access to information. I employ a comparative political science analysis that discusses democracy as a system of intellectual requirements that need to be fulfilled in order to function in a network society. 
My research traces the study of digital cultures and suggests a reallocation of power from government back to citizens in the nexus between the physical and digital space of protest. Furthermore, I interrogate whether there is a new socio-political framework that arises from this and whether this framework bases itself on the political structure of western democracy or whether South Africa has shifted into an autocratic state.
 I explore the relationship between digital activism as a form of protest against political elites who use classification of information to conduct corrupt activities. I achieve this through a critical exploration of media reports, South African legislation on communicative freedom and free speech activist groups such as The Right 2 Know Campaign and the SOS Coalition.","award_title":"","award_institution":"University of Cape Town","award_department":"","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/brevis-chad-c.jpg","related_competitions":"Next Generation Social Sciences in Africa: Doctoral Dissertation Proposal Fellowship","fellow_topics":"","authors":null,"primary_author":null,"publish_date":null,"publisher":null,"s3azure_image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/brevis-chad-c.jpg","s3azure_pdf_url":null,"type":null,"post_year":2021,"content":"Chad Brevis is a PhD student in the Centre for Film & Media Studies at the University of Cape Town specializing in socio-political disapprobation to freedom of speech and the rise of online ‘hacktivism’ culture in a digital democracy. During his undergraduate and honors years, he worked as a tutor for the Department of Religion and Theology specializing in ethical theory. Brevis currently works as a tutor in the Department of English at the University of the Western Cape and also as an e-tutor for English at UNISA. His work experience includes journalism, editing, literary critique, and activism for the NGO The Right2Know Campaign, defending freedom of speech.
   Brevis completed a Master’s degree in English iterature as a full dissertation with a focus on 20th century literature, taboo topics in fiction, totalitarian censorship law, sociolinguistics, and ethics in literature. He also completed a MA qualification in realizing rights and social justice as well as violent conflict, media, and the politics of representation from the Institute of Social Studies in The Netherlands. Accolades are as follows:
    Activist/academic researcher /editor for the Right 2 Know Campaign;
    Member of the Golden Key International Honors Society;
    Mellon Fellowship recipient and fellow;
    DAAD-NRF bursary holder for 2012-2014;
    Abe Bailey Europe Travel Bursary holder for emerging leaders and academics in Africa;
    SKILLS MA scholarship holder for master’s and Doctoral studies at The Institute of Social Studies in The Hague;
    Social Science Research Council: Next Generation Social Sciences in Africa Fellow (2018; 2019);
    Author of the academic book: Taboo Topics in Fiction: The Case of Vladimir Nabokov's Lolita.","record_index":0,"objectID":"9777-0","_snippetResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Chad Brevis","matchLevel":"none"},"content":{"value":"… emerging leaders and academics in Africa;
