 Elgeyo Marakwet County, Kenya makes a compelling case to policymakers for the need to decentralize the UNSCR 1325 to the grass root in order to achieve sustainable peace. Dr. Hamasi has published many books and articles in reputable journals. She has had visiting fellowships taking her to Sweden and Norway and is the Chief Executive Officer for the Nairobi-based Centre for Democracy Research and Development (CEDRED) and African Interdisciplinary Studies Association (AISA).  She serves on the editorial boards of the Journal ofPpopular Education in Africa (JOPEA) and the Journal of African Interdisciplinary Studies (JAIS).
Dr. Hamasi was a Guest Researcher at the Nordic Africa Institute (NAI) in Sweden where she carried out a study on Radicalization of Women and Girls in Kenya and Implications for Peace and Security in Kenya, which explored the new trends of terrorism.","record_index":0,"objectID":"10276-0","_snippetResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Hamasi Linnet","matchLevel":"none"},"content":{"value":"Linnet Hamasi is a lecturer at Kenyatta University after previously working at Kisii University and the Catholic University of Eastern Africa. She holds a PhD in peace and conflict <em>studies</em> …","matchLevel":"partial"}},"_highlightResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Hamasi Linnet","matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[]},"content":{"value":"Linnet Hamasi is a lecturer at Kenyatta University after previously working at Kisii University and the Catholic University of Eastern Africa. She holds a PhD in peace and conflict <em>studies</em> from Masinde Muliro University of Science and Technology (MMUST), Kenya. She had earlier received a Bachelor’s Degree from Kenyatta University and a Master’s Degree from the Catholic University of Eastern Africa (CUEA). Her doctoral dissertation on Women’s Knowledge Systems and Peacebuilding among the Pastoral Communities of Kenya with a focus on Elgeyo Marakwet County, Kenya makes a compelling <em>case</em> to policymakers for the need to decentralize the UNSCR 1325 to the grass root in order to achieve sustainable peace. Dr. Hamasi has published many books and articles in reputable journals. She has had visiting fellowships taking her to Sweden and Norway and is the Chief Executive Officer for the Nairobi-based Centre for Democracy Research and Development (CEDRED) and African Interdisciplinary <em>Studies</em> Association (AISA).  She serves on the editorial boards of the Journal ofPpopular Education in Africa (JOPEA) and the Journal of African Interdisciplinary <em>Studies</em> (JAIS).
Dr. Hamasi was a Guest Researcher at the Nordic Africa Institute (NAI) in Sweden where she carried out a study on Radicalization of Women and Girls in Kenya and Implications for Peace and Security in Kenya, which explored the new trends of terrorism.","matchLevel":"full","fullyHighlighted":false,"matchedWords":["case","studies"]}}},{"post_id":10272,"post_type":"fellow","post_type_label":"Fellows","post_title":"Mohamed Bakhit","post_excerpt":"","post_date":1546300800,"post_date_formatted":"January 1, 2019","post_modified":1633563646,"comment_count":0,"menu_order":0,"post_author":{"user_id":1,"display_name":"ssrc_admin","user_url":"","user_login":"ssrc_admin"},"images":[],"permalink":"https://www.ssrc.org/fellows/396dfb00-776f-ea11-a811-000d3a3be5cf/","post_mime_type":"","taxonomies":[],"taxonomies_hierarchical":[],"is_sticky":0,"archived":"false","exclude_search":"false","program_types":"","competition_year":"2019","project_title":"South Sudanese Refugees in Sudan Border: community citizenship and refugee systems","project_description":"","award_title":"","award_institution":"University of Khartoum","award_department":"","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/bakhit-mohamed-abdelbagi-gismalla.jpg","related_competitions":"African Peacebuilding Network: Individual Research Fellowships","fellow_topics":"","authors":null,"primary_author":null,"publish_date":null,"publisher":null,"s3azure_image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/bakhit-mohamed-abdelbagi-gismalla.jpg","s3azure_pdf_url":null,"type":null,"post_year":2019,"content":"Mohamed Abdelbagi Gismalla Bakhit has a PhD in anthropology from the University of Bayreuth, Germany. The title of his 2015 thesis is“Identity and Lifestyles Construction in Multi-Ethnic Shantytowns: A Case Study of Al-Baraka Community in Khartoum, Sudan”. He has been an Assistant Professor in the Department of Sociology and Social Anthropology, Faculty of Economic and Social Studies at the University of Khartoum up until August 2016. Since February 2017, he is the Head of the Department of Sociology and Social Anthropology, Faculty of Economic & Social Studies at the University of Khartoum. Dr. Bakhit’s main research interests are identity change, urbanization, forced migration, minority groups, and citizenship. During the last three years, he has been a Postdoctoral Fellow at the Volkswagen Foundation working on a funded research project entitled “Knowledge for Tomorrow: Cooperative Research Projects in Sub-Saharan Africa,” coordinated by the Centre for Interdisciplinary African Studies (ZIAF) at the University of Frankfurt, Germany. His post doctoral project is entitled  “Identity, Nationality, and Citizenship for Southern Sudanese Communities in Khartoum and Juba.” The research project ran from 2015 to 2018.","record_index":0,"objectID":"10272-0","_snippetResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Mohamed Bakhit","matchLevel":"none"},"content":{"value":"… title of his 2015 thesis is“Identity and Lifestyles Construction in Multi-Ethnic Shantytowns: A <em>Case</em> Study of Al-Baraka Community in Khartoum, Sudan”. He has been an Assistant Professor …","matchLevel":"partial"}},"_highlightResult":{"post_title":{"value":"Mohamed Bakhit","matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[]},"content":{"value":"Mohamed Abdelbagi Gismalla Bakhit has a PhD in anthropology from the University of Bayreuth, Germany. The title of his 2015 thesis is“Identity and Lifestyles Construction in Multi-Ethnic Shantytowns: A <em>Case</em> Study of Al-Baraka Community in Khartoum, Sudan”. He has been an Assistant Professor in the Department of Sociology and Social Anthropology, Faculty of Economic and Social <em>Studies</em> at the University of Khartoum up until August 2016. Since February 2017, he is the Head of the Department of Sociology and Social Anthropology, Faculty of Economic & Social <em>Studies</em> at the University of Khartoum. Dr. Bakhit’s main research interests are identity change, urbanization, forced migration, minority groups, and citizenship. During the last three years, he has been a Postdoctoral Fellow at the Volkswagen Foundation working on a funded research project entitled “Knowledge for Tomorrow: Cooperative Research Projects in Sub-Saharan Africa,” coordinated by the Centre for Interdisciplinary African <em>Studies</em> (ZIAF) at the University of Frankfurt, Germany. His post doctoral project is entitled  “Identity, Nationality, and Citizenship for Southern Sudanese Communities in Khartoum and Juba.” The research project ran from 2015 to 2018.","matchLevel":"full","fullyHighlighted":false,"matchedWords":["case","studies"]}}},{"post_id":9630,"post_type":"fellow","post_type_label":"Fellows","post_title":"Chad Brevis","post_excerpt":"","post_date":1514764800,"post_date_formatted":"January 1, 2018","post_modified":1633563570,"comment_count":0,"menu_order":0,"post_author":{"user_id":1,"display_name":"ssrc_admin","user_url":"","user_login":"ssrc_admin"},"images":[],"permalink":"https://www.ssrc.org/fellows/88a4043a-10c5-e911-a99d-000d3a37d634/","post_mime_type":"","taxonomies":[],"taxonomies_hierarchical":[],"is_sticky":0,"archived":"false","exclude_search":"false","program_types":"","competition_year":"2019","project_title":"Communicative Freedom in a Digital Democracy: Political and Economic Resistance to Free Speech and the Rise of Digital Activism in South Africa.","project_description":"My research focuses on a discourse analysis of violent conflict in protests, media and the politics of representation. It explores the idea of South Africa as a democracy, and how the language of communicative legislation at once promotes and inhibits communicative freedom. 
My analysis discusses democracy as a system of requirements that need to be fulfilled to be considered as functional. I intend to trace the study of digital cultures within social media to suggest a reallocation of power from government back to citizens in the nexus between the physical and digital space of protest. 
An innovative aspect of my thesis is the exploration of digital activism in South Africa. I argue that institutionalised corruption is condoned into existence due to misappropriation of communicative legislations. I aim to show that the misappropriation of the Promotion of Access to Information Act and the Protection of Personal Information Act undermines communicative freedom as enshrined within the South African Constitution.","award_title":"","award_institution":"University of Cape Town","award_department":"Department of English","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/brevis-chad-c.jpg","related_competitions":"Next Generation Social Sciences in Africa: Doctoral Dissertation Research Fellowship","fellow_topics":"","authors":null,"primary_author":null,"publish_date":null,"publisher":null,"s3azure_image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/ssrc-cdn1/crmuploads/contact/brevis-chad-c.jpg","s3azure_pdf_url":null,"type":null,"post_year":2018,"content":"Chad Brevis is a PhD student in the Centre for Film & Media Studies at the University of Cape Town specializing in socio-political disapprobation to freedom of speech and the rise of online ‘hacktivism’ culture in a digital democracy. During his undergraduate and honors years, he worked as a tutor for the Department of Religion and Theology specializing in ethical theory. Brevis currently works as a tutor in the Department of English at the University of the Western Cape and also as an e-tutor for English at UNISA. His work experience includes journalism, editing, literary critique, and activism for the NGO The Right2Know Campaign, defending freedom of speech.
   Brevis completed a Master’s degree in English iterature as a full dissertation with a focus on 20th century literature, taboo topics in fiction, totalitarian censorship law, sociolinguistics, and ethics in literature. He also completed a MA qualification in realizing rights and social justice as well as violent conflict, media, and the politics of representation from the Institute of Social Studies in The Netherlands. Accolades are as follows:
